english:
  title: In the Gengzi Year, Attending Court Before the Mongols, Passing Through Western Capital
  author: Kim Gu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A small boat cuts across the green river's flow,
    As twilight brings me to the desolate Changqing Temple.
    Mournful verses rise to lament these mountains and streams—
    Perhaps the earth's own spirit weeps in secret sorrow.

    I recall when I carried my books to seek a distant master,
    And witnessed the Western Capital in its fullest glory.
    When moonlight blessed ten thousand homes that knew not how to bar their doors,
    And nine great avenues lay so clean that nothing lay unclaimed.

    Yet now those days seem swept away like dust,
    And pity fills my heart—the palace walls stand bare beneath the grass.
    The plow and harrow have carved through half of what were heroes' halls,
    While hemp and barley spread across the courts and marketplace.

    Where now is the maiden in her crimson skirt who gathered mulberry leaves?
    Her mournful song rises—and my heart grows old with sorrow.
  footnotes:
    - The Gengzi year refers to 1420, during Korea's Joseon Dynasty. The reference to attending court before the Mongols indicates this poem reflects on a period of foreign dominance.
    - Changqing Temple (長慶寺) was a Buddhist temple in Gyeongju, Korea's ancient capital (the 'Western Capital' of the poem), which had suffered decline.
    - The contrast between the remembered prosperity of the Western Capital and its present ruin forms the emotional core of the poem, expressing both nostalgia and lamentation.
